{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6ab9a842-b9fe-4dce-9124-400c88069f9f","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface**:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`, etc.).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n3. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into classes that need file access (constructor injection).\n4. **In tests**, pass a fake/mock `IFileSystem` — no disk I/O needed.\n\nAlternatively, use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package, which provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface wrapping all of `System.IO`, plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing.\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: Roll your own\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n\n// Option B: Use the NuGet package\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```\n\n`System.IO.Abstractions` is the most popular choice — it saves you from maintaining the interface yourself and covers edge cases you'd otherwise miss.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"db38b2fc-3f15-47b8-aa44-625ab9bd0d5b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"481D:1C33BD:606FB02:68674E8:69FBF251"},"id":"ae83108a-93e0-4514-bcfd-3fa7454c1885","timestamp":"2026-05-07T02:00:58.187Z","parentId":"439dfafb-f0b3-4b8a-ac41-e08183410228"}
